  <row>
    <panel>
      <html>
        <b>Path to ingestion blockage</b>
      <p>This view walks through the various metrics being used to investigate data ingestion congestion issues.</p>
      <hr/>
      <p>1st panel: Congestion begins at the Replication queue getting blocked.</p>
      <p>2nd panel: The indexing queue begins to block when the Replication queue does not recover. This is the lowest level queue in the data ingestion pipeline.</p>
      <p>3rd panel: Forwarder port (data ingestion) closes when the ingestion queue doesn't recover and queues above it (typing, aggregation and finally parsing) fill up. When we can no longer put new data into any of the ingestion queues, tcpin_queue is now full. From there, kernel TCP buffers start to fill and when those are filled, the port stops accepting new data and forwarders can no longer connect to it.</p>
      <p>The ideal state is when all 3 panels are empty.</p>
      <p>Bonus: Additional under-the-covers details are <a href="http://wiki.splunk.com/images/f/f0/Splunk_EventProcessing_v15_0_Indexer.pdf">here</a>.</p>
    </html>
    </panel>
  </row>
